  "prompt": "Why does Audible.com take away all my credits when my membership expires? Didn't I pay for those credits last year?",
  "response": "When you purchase a membership with Audible.com, the credits you receive are part of the benefits of having an active subscription. These credits are essentially prepaid vouchers for audiobooks and are tied to your membership status. Here's a breakdown of why Audible takes away unused credits when your membership expires:\n\n1. **Terms of Service**: Audible's terms of service clearly state that unused credits may expire if the membership is not maintained. This is outlined when you sign up and agree to the conditions of the subscription.\n\n2. **Membership Benefit**: Credits are considered a benefit of an ongoing membership. Just like monthly subscription services, the benefits are active as long as the membership is active. When the membership lapses, the benefits, including unused credits, are terminated.\n\n3. **Economy Model**: Audible uses a subscription-based model where members are encouraged to use their credits within the subscription period. This model ensures that users stay engaged and maintain their subscription.\n\n4. **Expiration Policy**: Audible makes it clear that credits have an expiration date, which aligns with the membership duration. This encourages users to utilize their credits promptly rather than accumulating them indefinitely.\n\nYes, you paid for those credits as part of your membership fee, but the credits are tied to your active membership status. If the membership expires, the credits typically expire along with it due to the terms and conditions agreed upon during sign-up.\n\nTo avoid losing credits, it's best to use them before your membership ends or consider renewing your membership if you want to keep the unused credits. Additionally, you can contact Audible customer service for potential solutions or clarifications regarding your specific situation.",
